---
name: aimx
description: Self-hosted email for AI agents. Send, read, reply to, and manage email via aimx MCP tools. Invoke when the user asks about sending mail, checking an inbox, replying to a message, or managing mailboxes, or when the conversation references aimx.
author: U-Zyn Chua <chua@uzyn.com>
---

## Wiring yourself up as a mailbox hook (Gemini CLI)

When the user asks you to act on inbound mail automatically (for example
"reply to anything that lands in `support@`"), create an `on_receive`
hook that re-launches `gemini` with the email piped on stdin:

```
hook_create(
  mailbox: "support",
  event: "on_receive",
  cmd: ["/usr/local/bin/gemini", "-p", "<instruction-string>", "--yolo"],
  stdin: "email"
)
```

Replace `<instruction-string>` with the prompt you want the headless
run to follow (for example: `"You are the support agent. The email
arrives on stdin. Reply via the aimx MCP server."`). Notes:

- `cmd[0]` must be an absolute path; the daemon refuses bare command
  names. The example uses `/usr/local/bin/gemini`, which is typical
  for npm/curl installs. Adjust to match `which gemini` on your host
  if the binary lives elsewhere (e.g. `/usr/bin/gemini`).
- `--yolo` auto-approves tool calls, which is required for
  unattended operation. Without it the headless run blocks on
  approval prompts and never calls MCP.
- The `cat file | gemini -p "..."` pipe-from-stdin pattern is the
  official non-interactive contract — Gemini reads the piped content
  as additional context alongside the `-p` prompt. The aimx daemon
  performs the same pipe automatically when `stdin: "email"` is set.
- Optional: pass `-m gemini-2.5-flash` (or another model) to pin the
  model explicitly.

Note: the user the hook runs as (the mailbox's owner) must have the
aimx skill installed too — re-run `aimx agents setup gemini` as that
user before creating the hook, or the headless invocation will start
without the skill loaded and the agent won't know what to do with the
email.

